Hi Friends, such sad news.  The great running champion Murray Halberg has passed away. He was an  inspiration to many and gave back hugely to the sport. We stand on the shoulders of people like this. Please read Roger Robinson's beautiful tribute below and on Facebook. 

“I just learned of the death of Murray Halberg. He was one of my few lifetime heroes. I feel, as Shakespeare said, "There is nothing left remarkable beneath the visiting moon." I have researched and written an obituary, which I will post here when it is publlshed. But my personal tribute was in "When Running Made History," the chapter that gave my eye-witness description of Halberg’s thrilling (truly thrilling) Olympic 5000 metres win in 1960. This is how I ended the chapter: 
"I need to add a personal note.  If Snell’s godlike power filled me with awe, Halberg had me out there sharing his black shorts and thrashing my own skinny body round the track.  Whenever I am asked the greatest race I have ever seen, even now, almost sixty years later, I say unhesitatingly “Halberg's 5,000 at Rome.” As a runner born with no fast-twitch fibres, who would never win any race on the finishing sprint, I was watching a man win in a way that might perhaps be my way, if I could ever make myself strong enough in lung and leg and will.  My best later track victories later in the 1960s and '70s were won Halberg’s way, breaking away with two or three laps to go. Surprise them. Steal the gap. Give every drop to keep it. 

When I think of Murray Halberg, I am still the admiring student in the cheap section of the stand, hoarsely shouting his name as he won, one hot afternoon in Rome in 1960.”

What a great article about a great woman, Beth Schluger, race director and event organizer extraordinaire....written by another great woman--Lori Riley, superwoman journalist from the @HartfordCourant! Beth Schluger should only retire to have fun as she worked tirelessly to create events like the Hartford Marathon (@HMFEvents that brought positive attention and revenue to the city.  All the while she was a huge activist for fitness and women's rights, and it was a joy working with her in the early days of women's running.  Our Avon Race in the 90s not only brought Grete Waitz, but also Bill Rodgers' 65+ year old mom! And Lori, please don't retire yet, girl!! Journalism needs your voice badly to continue covering incredible stories of women's achievements from around the world. Your voice has helped make the Global Sisterhood a powerful reality.  Bravo to you both!

I just lost one of my best friends, but the whole world has lost one of the kindest, most loyal, and most persistently dedicated women ever:  Cathy Troisi. Cathy started jogging in her 40s and got hooked on it. She became one of the most prolific of marathoners and ultra runners, doing something like 490 marathons. When her only child, her daughter died of cancer, the balm of running and the running community saved Cathy's sanity. Cathy quit her job and dedicated herself to helping to raise her grandchildren and also to raising money for the Dana Farber Cancer Center.  She was a fixture at the @BostonMarathon every year and personally raised something like $230,000 over the course of her participation. She was passionate and dedicated, never quitting and always pressing on with long races all over the USA.  I met her at Boston in 1998, and we became fast  friends, hilariously so when she nominated me 13 times to the National Women's Hall of Fame, and then was there, with bells and tears, when I got inducted in 2011. Last week she was on vacation in Hawaii with her beloved and now-grown granddaughter Ashley. They ran a 5K there together on Sunday, flew home to Albany, NY, and Cathy said she didn't feel well and wanted to lie down.  She passed away in her sleep of heart failure.  For someone who worked so hard and gave so much, I am glad that the Universe has graced her with such a sweet and gentle death. You deserve the best, dear Cathy, for all you have given all of us. Rest In Peace.
(Photos: Cathy, her runner friend Scott and me at National Women's Hall of Fame induction 2011; Cathy and me at an autograph signing at the National Distance Running Hall of Fame; and in 2020, being greeted by granddaughter, Ashley after finishing the Virtual Boston Marathon).
Love, @KathrineSwitzer

Today it’s 93F/34C, and the course is hilly, broken, varied in surface, full of corners and bumps, and unrelentingly demanding. Dave Katz, course consultant for World Athletics, told me the policy now for the WXC is to make each course a unique talking point. I endorse that, but regret that my runs in the main championship in the 1960s-70s were on boring horserace circuits.  I would have loved this one, until my knees retired. Watching the schools races today, we saw one African interrupt a gentle warm-up jog to bound joyfully up the course’s steepest hill, one that’s likely to take me about two minutes on Sunday morning. When a pair of deadly bombs exploded near the finish line of the 2013 Boston Marathon, Joann Flaminio was initially unsure if the iconic race would ever be run again. As the first female president of the Boston Athletic Association, it was her job to rebuild runners’ confidence in the event and make the next version a display of strength and resilience. She found the conviction to do that after getting a message from someone she barely knew, telling her that Boston was not alone—that people around the world were supporting the city. As she explains in today’s episode of The Daily Rally podcast, the experience helped her see the impact of simple acts of kindness. It’s a lesson she’s held onto as a global advocate for @261fearless, a non-profit that works to create safe spaces for women to grow and learn through community running events.

Soooo excited for Friday evening in Seneca Falls when I lead this group of INCREDIBLE women as we march together in Seneca Falls to officially open the 2023 ERA Convention, on the exact date of the 100th anniversary of the first ERA convention.  Another first:  I was the first torch runner for the ERA torch relay in 1977 from Seneca Falls to the International Women's Conference in Houston....and what a joy and privilege to bear the torch there again, 46 years later, in the same shorts and Women On The Move tee shirt. 

https://www.fingerlakesdailynews.com/local/ontario-seneca-wayne/seneca-falls-march-for-the-era-friday-night

Confirmed speakers for our ERA March & Rally on July 21st, 2023 include: Ann Fuller, Granddaughter of Crystal Eastman; Coline Jenkins, Great, great granddaughter of Elizabeth Cady Stanton; Kate Kelly, Author & ERA Convention Lead Organizer; Julie Suk, Author & Constitutional Attorney; Alissa Hunt & Rachel Rupison, Alice Paul Institute; Ellie Smeal, Feminist Leader/Grassroots Organizer; Zakiya Thomas, ERA Coalition/Fund for Women’s Equality; Carolyn Maloney & Christina Nunes, NYS & National NOW; and Anna Dobrot, Co-author, 2020 Youth Declaration of Sentiments.

I am wearing the same shorts and shirt that I wore in 1977 to lead the famous torch run across America for the ERA Amendment proposal that year to the women’s conference in Houston. I was honored to be the first torch bear out of Seneca Falls in 1977, and I am so honored to be the torch bearer again to lead the marchers into the speaking park, and then pass the torch to the next generation. The other women in the March picture include in the white suit, about 5 foot 4, is Kathy Hochul, the governor of New York; and also the tall black woman is Letitia James, the Attorney, General of New York state! Both of these women gave fiery speeches and really ignited us! Next to me in the antique black dress is Melinda, (I do not know her last name )who is dressed as Elizabeth Cady Stanton, the great suffragist pioneer, who lived here in Seneca Falls. She was a partner to Susan B, Anthony, and the great first women’s movement.
Cheers @KathrineSwitzer

Running legend @kathrineswitzer is gearing up to rock bib number 261 on October 7! 💪 Pairing an iconic women's event with a lifelong advocate for women's empowerment, Switzer is ready to hit the pavement and join thousands of women in this historic race. 🙌 

Switzer’s trailblazing career began at the 1967 Boston Marathon, when she became the first woman to wear a bib number and complete the historic race. Donning bib number 261, images of Switzer’s encounter with a disgruntled race director during the event were spread globally and helped launch a revolution for women’s participation in sports. It was out of this revolution that races like the Boston 10K for Women began. 

In 2016, Switzer launched @261fearless, a global non-profit committed to empowering women through running. At 76, Switzer is still a force, relentlessly working to create opportunities for women. We can't wait to see her October 7! 💙🏃‍♀️

Post #2: Got to hang out with my #shero Kathrine Switzer Marathon Woman! Spent an August weekend in New Paltz, NY with the iconic "K.V. Switzer" & her hubby Roger. (Who is equally amazing). Those of you who read STAND know Kathrine was hugely influential to me in 2009, when I brought her my first business proposal for women at the Tour de France. Kathrine mentored me, believed in me, and helped me gain confidence that I was doing the right thing in lobbying for women's inclusion at the TdF. 

Not only was it great to be back in New Paltz after 14 years, but also a bit emotional. Guess who came with me to first meet Kathrine in 2009? My dad, Peter K Bertine Sr. We all had lunch together at Kathrine & Roger's home, going over my proposal. With my father and Kathrine both being Syracuse students at the same time in the mid-1960s (law school Dad, undergrad KVS), he was a huge fan of what she accomplished. I don't have a photo/selfie from our pre-smartphone time together in 2009, but no doubt Dad is smiling down. Oh, and Dad, please keep smiling/watching because...

I'm gonna run the New York City Marathon in November with Kathrine's amazing charity team @261Fearless! 🏃🏻‍♀️❤️🙏 Honored to be part of her foundation which empowers & creates running opportunities for women around the world. Think about it: We're pretty lucky most U.S. locations are safe for women to run, but not every country or community in the world offers safe harbor women runners. Kathrine Switzer's #261fearless is changing that, 19 nations strong, and I'm so proud to be part of anything this woman does. 

Thank you, Switzer. See ya next month at NYCM!* 

*NYC friends, we'll be on a panel discussion together in Manhattan on Sat Nov 4. Details to come. Stay tuned. I'd love to see you there!

Sharing from Roger’s post, this is our new (American) fireplace, designed and made by Jack Pishkur, who found and treated the beam and the slate, and forged the bronze vents from runner designs Roger suggested. (Previously, it was just four ugly grill vents.) The painting above is by Leonid Hushcha, Ukrainian-American artist working in Minneapolis. Jack Pishkur’s masterly bronze fireplace images are (top left, clockwise) Roger winning the New Zealand Masters cross-country, me finishing second at Boston with a PR in 1975, dolichos (distance) runners on an ancient Greek vase, and Atalanta figure from Leonid Hushcha’s “Running Courtship.” Roger has always been interested in the links between running and art or literature, and about five years ago put a “running in art calendar” on Facebook. This new, fine, and useful piece of running art gives us pleasure every evening when in our NY home, especially as warm air comes out of those runner vents.
Cheers @KathrineSwitzer

She won her Olympic medals in 1984 in Los Angeles (bronze) and 1988 in Seoul (gold).
